(   )  ,
where  denotes anti-time ordering. This is unambiguously defined
if both  or both . Problems arise
when  and .

Let us see what this means for the point particles in the figures.
In Figure , we launch the particle and its image from 
and , and then propagate them using 
towards the -axis, i.e.  up to . This gives
the lower half and the upper half of the forward and backward
trajectories of Fig. . They are identified on the
fundamental domain,
so  this gives the "downward" trajectory on the left part
in Figure  all the way to the marked point S, and the downward
trajectory to the point S on the front fold of the pocket in
Figure . Similarly, we could propagate forward and backward
from , giving the other halves of the trajectories
in Figure . In Figure , the resulting
trajectory is the "upward"
one on the left diagram, and the upward trajectory starting on the rear
fold and continuing to the front fold of the pocket.

To summarize,
on the fundamental domain (the pocket), we can either choose the time
to point downwards, corresponding to Figure  b) with
the arrows reversed, and consider time evolution up to a "big
crunch" at , or choose the time to point upwards and consider
time evolution forward from a "big bang". The latter
corresponds to Figure  b). Either way, the evolution breaks
down at . But that is also the point where from Section we know the stress tensor to diverge(Similar analysis, based
on the other two choices of the fundamental domain, Figure a) and c),
are also possible. Then the time evolution would break down at 
(a) or at null cone (c).) .

Consider then an interacting field theory. We could adopt the
interaction picture, and define the time evolution operator as
 &&  U_I,inv  (t_0,t_1) = 

